<Base title="About — Hankyeol Kyung">
  <h1>About</h1>

  <p>
    I'm an agent engineer building AI systems that work in practice --
    not polished demos, but tools and infrastructure people actually rely on.
    The problems I care about sit at the intersection of memory, autonomy,
    and how agents fit into real human workflows.
  </p>

  <p>
    At <a href="https://asleep.ai">Asleep</a>, I build AI-powered sleep products --
    voice agents, ambient sensing, and the infrastructure connecting them.
    Outside of work, I build personal systems that treat agents as collaborators:
    external memory, knowledge retrieval, structured agent control, and ambient interfaces.
  </p>

  <h2>How I think about systems</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Harness over model.</strong>
    In applied agent work, capability depends less on the model than on
    the harness built around it -- tool integration, runtime environments,
    context packaging, evaluation loops, session handling.
    A better harness makes the same model dramatically more useful.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Interface bridges over substrate.</strong>
    A powerful system with a bad entry point won't get used.
    Sometimes the right move is not replacing the backend, but changing the surface exposed on top of it.
    Knowledge graphs surfaced as wiki pages. Agent runtimes exposed through CLI.
    The best system is the one whose interface invites use.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Structured control over prompting.</strong>
    Agents are not just something you prompt -- they are sessions, runtime objects,
    things that can be resumed, steered, inspected, and automated.
    This distinction matters once you care about real reliability.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Memory as both knowledge and runtime.</strong>
    Agent memory is not only a storage problem. It is also a runtime UX problem --
    thread continuity, session state, context correctness.
    A strong personal agent is model + memory substrate + maintenance loop,
    not just a smart chat endpoint.
  </p>

  <h2>Principles</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Ship over polish. Real users over toy demos.</li>
    <li>Good infrastructure disappears into the workflow.</li>
    <li>Agents should extend how you think, not replace it.</li>
    <li>The best agent systems are collaborative, not theatrical.</li>
    <li>Private knowledge layer upstream, curated public layer downstream.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Interests</h2>
  <p>
    Multi-agent orchestration. File-based agent memory systems.
    Graph-mediated retrieval over raw traversal.
    The gap between agent demos and agent products.
    AI-native workflows that respect the human in the loop.
    Turning scattered context into reusable knowledge.
  </p>
</Base>
